  "prompt": "Is the body of the Prophet Muhammad (PBUH) still untouched in his tomb in Madinah? Has anyone ever seen the body since his burial in 632?",
  "response": "The Prophet Muhammad (PBUH) was buried in his chamber (Hujrah) within the Masjid al-Nabawi in Madinah after his passing in 632 CE. His body rests in a grave that was originally simple and unmarked, as was the custom at the time. Over the centuries, the area around his grave, known as the Rawdah, has been enclosed and expanded as part of the mosque complex.\n\nThere is no historical or verified record indicating that the Prophet's (PBUH) body has been exhumed or physically examined since his burial. Islamic tradition holds that the Prophet's (PBUH) body remains undisturbed in his tomb, and it is considered sacred and revered by Muslims. The sanctity of his resting place is maintained, and access to the chamber is strictly controlled. Only certain scholars and caretakers have access to the inner areas, and even they do not interact with the grave itself in a manner that would disturb it.\n\nMuslims believe that the Prophet (PBUH) is in a state of *barzakh* (the intermediary stage between death and the Day of Judgment), and his body is not subject to decay as with ordinary human remains. This belief is based on various Islamic texts and interpretations.\n\nIn summary, there is no evidence or record that the Prophet's (PBUH) body has been seen or disturbed since his burial, and Islamic tradition holds that it remains untouched in his tomb.",
